doc.ContractDescription: FRONTAL EVENTS ARE IMPRESSIVE MANIFESTATIONS OF MARTIAN EXTRA-TROPICAL CYCLONES WHICH PLAY IMPORTANT ROLES IN ATMOSPHERIC ENERGY AND MOMENTUM TRANSPORTS AND CONSTITUENT DISTRIBUTIONS. FRONTAL EVENTS ARE SENSITIVE INDICATORS OF THE GLOBAL CIRCULATION. THEY RESPOND PROMPTLY TO CHANGES INDUCED BY GLOBAL DUST STORMS. AT THE SAME TIME, THEY ARE LINKED WITH SEVERAL IMPORTANT CIRCULATION COMPONENTS (INCLUDING TRAVELING WAVES, THERMAL TIDES, THE HADLEY CIRCULATION AND STATIONARY WAVES), AND CAN LEAD TO MAJOR DUST STORMS THROUGH REPEATED RUSHING DUST STORMS. PREVIOUS STUDIES USING MGS MOC AND TES DATA HAVE ESTABLISHED ABOUT FOUR MARS YEARS OF FRONTAL EVENT RECORD, REVEALING RICH PATTERNS AND VARIABILITIES IN THE SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL DISTRIBUTIONS. THIS PROPOSAL WILL EXTEND AND EXPAND STUDIES OF FRONTAL EVENTS TO MRO MARCI AND MCS DATA. SPECIFICALLY, THE MORPHOLOGIES, DEVELOPMENT HISTORIES, MOTIONS, TIMING, POSITIONS, LIFETIMES, ORIENTATIONS, AREAS AND COMPOSITIONS WILL BE ARCHIVED USING MARCI MARS DAILY GLOBAL MAPS (MDGM)SPECIALLY MADE FOR STUDYING FRONTAL EVENTS, THE OPACITIES, TEMPERATURE ANOMALIES, AND WAVE MODES WILL BE EXAMINED USING THE CORRESPONDING MCS DERIVED DATA, THE RESPONSE OF FRONTAL EVENTS TO MAJOR DUST STORMS WILL BE DOCUMENTED, THE EFFECTS OF FRONTAL EVENTS ON TRACER DISTRIBUTIONS WILL BE EVALUATED, THE INTERACTIONS BETWEEN FRONTAL EVENTS AND GLOBAL CIRCULATION WILL BE EXAMINED, AND THE RESULTS WILL BE COMPARED WITH PREVIOUS MGS RESULTS. THE BY-PRODUCT OF THIS PROPOSAL, THE MARCI MDGM, WILL BE FREELY SHARED WITH THE COMMUNITY OVER THE INTERNET AS BEFORE. THIS PROPOSAL WILL HELP MAINTAIN A LONG TERM CONSISTENT RECORD OF MARTIAN WEATHER AND CLIMATE. IT WILL ALSO EXPAND PREVIOUS STUDIES TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF THE HIGHER VERTICAL RESOLUTION OF MCS LIMB SOUNDINGS AND THE AVAILABILITY OF UV IMAGES. RESULTS CAN BE USED BY NUMERICAL MODELS TO VALIDATE SIMULATIONS, IMPROVE PHYSICAL PARAMETERIZATIONS, EXPLORE SENSITIVITIES AND TEST HYPOTHESES. THIS PROPOSAL WILL LEAD TO A BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE MARTIAN ATMOSPHERE, ENHANCING THE SCIENTIFIC RETURNS OF THE MRO MISSION. IT FITS THE SCOPE OF THE MARS DATA ANALYSIS PROGRAM AND IS RELEVANT TO NASA'S STRATEGIC GOAL 3.

doc.ContractDescription: WE PROPOSE TO IMPROVE THE ANGULAR RESOLUTION OF THE MOST WIDELY USED MAP OF GALACTIC DUST BY AN ORDER OF MAGNITUDE USING MID-IR DATA. IN APRIL, 2011, THE WIDE-FIELD INFRARED SURVEY EXPLORER (WISE) SATELLITE RELEASED A PRELIMINARY ATLAS COVERING 57% OF THE SKY IN 4 PASSBANDS. THE 12 MICRON BAND REVEALS INTRICATE DUST CLOUDS AND FILAMENTS ONLY HINTED AT IN THE SFD MAP. EVEN THOUGH IT TRACES PAH EMISSION RATHER THAN THE LARGE GRAINS RESPONSIBLE FOR EXTINCTION, THE MUCH HIGHER RESOLUTION MAKES POSSIBLE A NUMBER OF IMPROVEMENTS IN OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION AND PROPERTIES OF GALACTIC DUST. OUR THREE MAIN GOALS ARE: 1. TO ADDRESS THE TEMPORAL VARIATION OF THE ZODIACAL FOREGROUNDS BY CALIBRATING THE OFFSET OF THE WISE DATA TO IRAS AND DIRBE DATA. THIS WILL RESULT IN AN ABSOLUTE BRIGHTNESS CALIBRATED ATLAS AT 12 MICRONS, WHICH WILL BE VALUABLE FOR THE STUDY OF PAH EMISSION IN THE DIFFUSE ISM. 2. TO RECALIBRATE THE HIGH SPATIAL FREQUENCY POWER IN THE 12 MICRON MAPS TO MATCH SFD DUST COLUMN DENSITY, ON WAVENUMBERS WHERE BOTH ARE MEASURED. BY MERGING THE LARGER SCALES OF SFD WITH THE FINE DETAILS FROM WISE, WE CAN OBTAIN A HYBRID SFD-LIKE MAP WITH AN ORDER OF MAGNITUDE BETTER SPATIAL RESOLUTION. 3. PAN-STARRS HAS ALREADY MEASURED OF ORDER 1 BILLION STARS IN 5 PHOTOMETRIC BANDS ACROSS 3/4 OF THE SKY. USING THESE STARS AS BACKLIGHTS, WE WILL EVALUATE THE IMPROVED DUST MAP AND (HOPEFULLY) VERIFY THAT THE INCREASED RESOLUTION DOES IMPROVE EXTINCTION ESTIMATES. THE SFD MAP WAS ORIGINALLY CONCEIVED AS A MAP OF THE DUST FOREGROUND INTERFERING WITH COSMOLOGICAL OBSERVATIONS (E.G. LARGE-SCALE STRUCTURE) AT HIGH GALACTIC LATITUDES. IT HAS SINCE FOUND A WIDE RANGE OF USES IN ALL PARTS OF THE SKY, AND FROM RADIO WAVES TO GAMMA-RAYS. AS COSMOLOGY EXPERIMENTS BECOME INCREASINGLY SENSITIVE TO STRUCTURES ON SMALL SCALES, THE DETAILED DISTRIBUTION OF DUST WILL BECOME INCREASINGLY IMPORTANT. BY COMBINING ARCHIVAL DATA SETS WITH RECENT DATA FROM WISE, WE WILL CREATE AN UPDATED FULL-SKY DUST MAP WITH UNPARALLELED RESOLUTION AND SENSITIVITY. WE WILL ALSO OPEN THE DOORS TO STUDYING THE DUST TEMPERATURE, PAH FRACTION, AND RADIATION FIELD ACROSS THE WHOLE SKY, COMPLEMENTING THE HIGHER RESOLUTION POINTED OBSERVATIONS BY SPITZER AND OTHER MISSIONS COVERING ONLY A TINY FRACTION OF THE SKY.

doc.ContractDescription: QUASI-PERIODIC OSCILLATIONS (QPOS) WITH LOW FREQUENCIES (0.01-70 HZ) HAVE BEEN OBSERVED IN THE X-RAY LIGHT CURVES OF MOST NEUTRON-STAR AND BLACK-HOLE LOW-MASS X-RAY BINARIES. DESPITE HAVING BEEN DISCOVERED MORE THAN 25 YEARS AGO, THEIR ORIGIN IS STILL NOT WELL UNDERSTOOD. SIMILARITIES BETWEEN THE LOW-FREQUENCY QPOS IN THE TWO TYPES OF SYSTEMS SUGGEST THAT THEY HAVE A COMMON ORIGIN IN THE ACCRETION FLOWS AROUND BLACK HOLES AND NEUTRON STARS. SOME OF THE PROPOSED MODELS THAT ATTEMPT TO EXPLAIN LOW-FREQUENCY QPOS INVOKE A GENERAL RELATIVISTIC EFFECT KNOWN AS LENSE-THIRRING PRECESSION (OR "FRAME DRAGGING"). HOWEVER, FOR LENSE-THIRRING PRECESSION TO PRODUCE SUBSTANTIAL MODULATIONS OF THE X-RAY FLUX THROUGH RELATIVISTIC BEAMING AND GRAVITATIONAL LENSING, THE ROTATION AXIS OF THE INNER PART OF THE ACCRETION DISK NEEDS TO HAVE A SUBSTANTIAL TILT (10-20 DEGREES) WITH RESPECT TO THE SPIN AXIS OF THE COMPACT OBJECT. WE ARGUE THAT OBSERVATIONAL EVIDENCE FOR SUCH TITLED INNER ACCRETION DISKS CAN BE FOUND IN THE VARIABILITY OF NEUTRON-STAR LOW-MASS X-RAY BINARIES THAT ARE VIEWED AT INCLINATION ANGLES OF 60-80 DEGREES. IN THESE SYSTEMS LOW-FREQUENCY QPOS AT ~0.1-15 HZ ARE OBSERVED THAT MODULATE THE EMISSION FROM THE NEUTRON STAR BY QUASI-PERIODIC OBSCURATION, PRESUMABLY BY A TITLED INNER DISC. THE GOAL OF OUR PROPOSED PROGRAM IS TO TEST WHETHER THE FREQUENCY EVOLUTION AND SPECTRAL STATE DEPENDENCE OF THESE QPOS IS SIMILAR TO WHAT IS OBSERVED FOR THE LOW-FREQUENCY QPOS THAT ARE OBSERVED IN LOWER-INCLINATION NEUTRON-STAR X-RAY BINARIES. TO MAKE SUCH A COMPARISON, WE NEED TO BETTER CHARACTERIZE THE PROPERTIES AND BEHAVIOR OF THESE QPOS. OUR STUDY WILL MAKE USE OF ALMOST 1300 RXTE OBSERVATIONS OF 11 SOURCES, TOTALING 5.7 MS OF DATA. SIGNATURES OF STRONG GRAVITY HAVE LONG BEEN SOUGHT AFTER IN ACCRETING COMPACT OBJECTS. WHILE STRONG EVIDENCE FROM SPECTRAL FEATURES HAS EMERGED IN THE LAST DECADE (E.G. GRAVITATIONALLY BROADENED IRON EMISSION LINES), THERE HAVE ONLY BEEN HINTS OF SUCH SIGNATURES FROM X-RAY VARIABILITY. IF IT CAN BE SHOWN THAT THE FREQUENCY EVOLUTION AND SPECTRAL STATE DEPENDENCE THE QPOS IN THE HIGH-INCLINATION SOURCES IS SIMILAR TO THAT OF THE LOW-FREQUENCY QPOS IN 'NORMAL' (LOWER-INCLINATION) NEUTRON-STAR X-RAY BINARIES, THIS WOULD LEND STRONG SUPPORT FOR LENSE-THIRRING PRECESSION MODELS. THIS WORK ADDRESSES GOALS LAID OUT IN NASA'S STRATEGIC PLAN. IN PARTICULAR, SINCE WE WILL STUDY THE CLOSE ENVIRONMENT AROUND BLACK HOLES AND NEUTRON STARS, IT IS HIGHLY RELEVANT TO OBJECTIVE 2.4.1: "IMPROVE UNDERSTANDING OF THE ORIGIN AND DESTINY OF THE UNIVERSE, AND THE NATURE OF BLACK HOLES, DARK ENERGY, DARK MATTER, AND GRAVITY".
